   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28606_1826_11_08_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Black-Castle_IE">Black Castle</placeName>
                  <lb/>
                  <date when="1826-11-08">Nov<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. 8<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1826</date>
                  <lb/>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                  D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Captain Beaufort</persName>
                  <lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               The bearer of this note is <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ThomJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.<lb/>
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Thompson</orig>
                     <reg>Thomson</reg>
                  </choice>
               </persName> - a Scotch gentleman<lb/>
               (very like <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntR1">Hunter</persName> I think in face &amp; something in manner<lb/>
               who lately came to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths<lb/>
               Town</placeName> &amp; finding none at home<lb/>
               there took the trouble of follow<lb/>
               ing me to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Black-Castle_IE">Black Castle</placeName> with<lb/>
               a strong letter of <choice>
                  <orig>recommenda<lb/>
                  tion</orig>
                  <reg>recommendation</reg>
               </choice> from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StewH1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Dugald Stewart</persName>
               <lb/>
               - He has been for several<lb/>
               years in South America<lb/>
               establishing schools in the<lb/>
               different states there - The<lb/>
               first by his own means <choice>
                  <orig>in-<lb/>
                  dependant</orig>
                  <reg>independent</reg>
               </choice> of <choice>
                  <abbr>Gov<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>.</abbr>
                  <reg>government</reg>
               </choice> assistance<lb/>
               - The success of this being spired<lb/>
               by newspapers The <choice>
                  <orig>govern-<lb/>
                  ments</orig>
                  <reg>governments</reg>
               </choice> of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#CL">Chile</placeName> - <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Buenos-Aires_AR">Buenos Ayres</placeName>
               <lb/>
               &amp;c invited him and gave<lb/>
               him aid to establish schools<lb/>
               in their countries - The priests<lb/>
               did not counteract him -<lb/>
               nor did they object to his giving<lb/>
               a selection of the scriptures<lb/>
               to be read in schools for Catholics<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28606_1826_11_08_page02.jpg"/>
               
               - There and many other curious<lb/>
               facts he will detail to you<lb/>
               - I just <del>suggest</del> first to you<lb/>
               what he has done &amp; you can<lb/>
               gather the rest from himself<lb/>
               - He likes to be questioned<lb/>
               answers questions well - and<lb/>
               cannot begin and tell unless<lb/>
               you put queries -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>His present object is to <choice>
                  <orig>esta-
                  -blish</orig>
                  <reg>establish</reg>
               </choice> an Irish &amp; English &amp; Scotch<lb/>
               colony in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#VE">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Venzuela</orig>
                     <reg>Venezuela</reg>
                  </choice>
               </placeName> - <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#GT">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Guatema<lb/>
                  -la</orig>
                     <reg>Guatemala</reg>
                  </choice>
               </placeName> or somewhere in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#MX">Mexico</placeName>
               <lb/>
               - <del>the</del> Education for said <choice>
                  <orig>colo<lb/>
                  -ny</orig>
                  <reg>colony</reg>
               </choice> to be as near perfection<lb/>
               as can be - <hi rend="underline">motto</hi>- - on which<lb/>
               he sets great store - "<hi rend="underline">We seek</hi>
               <lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">truth &amp; follow her</hi>" -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I question whether there<lb/>
               be not too much of the Scotch<lb/>
               metaphysician in his mind<lb/>
               for practice - but he has his<lb/>
               successful schools on his <choice>
                  <abbr>Cred<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
                  </abbr>
                  <reg>Credit</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
               side - according to his own <choice>
                  <orig>Acc<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>Account</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
               - We have not seen or heard the<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28606_1826_11_08_page03.jpg"/>
               
               other side -<lb/>
               He has a great deal of latent <choice>
                  <orig>enthu<lb/>
                  -siasm</orig>
                  <reg>enthusiasm</reg>
               </choice> - capable of being <unclear>evoked</unclear>
               <lb/>
               by friction - not by friction in<lb/>
               an opposite direction to his<lb/>
               habits &amp; wishes - but in the same<lb/>
               line - It is that sort of <choice>
                  <orig>non-appar-<lb/>
                  rent</orig>
                  <reg>non-apparent</reg>
               </choice>
               <add>cold</add> enthusiasm which ensures<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">perserverance</hi> - not to say <choice>
                  <orig>obsti<lb/>
                  -nacy</orig>
                  <reg>obstinacy</reg>
               </choice> - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DougT1">Lord Selkirk</persName> had it -<lb/>
               &amp; his answer to the very first<lb/>
               question I ever asked him<lb/>
               shewed how he valued it<lb/>
               "Is <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StewD1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Dugald Stewart</persName> an <choice>
                  <orig>enthu-<lb/>
                  siastic</orig>
                  <reg>enthusiastic</reg>
               </choice> person? -<lb/>
               - Not <hi rend="underline">apparently</hi> Madam.<lb/>
               - He is a great man<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Lady Hope whom I lately saw<lb/>
               &amp; who knows <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DougT1">the</persName>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DougJ1">Selkirks</persName> well told<lb/>
               me that when <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DougJ1">L<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. Selkirk</persName>s <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DougD1">son</persName>
               <lb/>
               a boy of 13 <del>first</del> heard of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WeddJ1">her father</persName>s<lb/>
               death one of his first <choice>
                  <orig>exclama-<lb/>
                  tions</orig>
                  <reg>exclamations</reg>
               </choice> was<lb/>
               What will become of <hi rend="underline">the</hi>
               <lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">Settlers</hi> -<lb/>
               meaning his fathers settlers<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>But to return to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ThomJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <choice>
                     <orig>Thomp-<lb/>
                  son</orig>
                     <reg>Thomson</reg>
                  </choice>
               </persName> - The only things I could do for him<lb/>
               was to give him <add>
                  <title ref="./Workography.xml#Early1">
                     <hi rend="underline">Early Lessons</hi>
                  </title> &amp;</add> a note of <choice>
                  <orig>introduct-<lb/>
                  tion</orig>
                  <reg>introduction</reg>
               </choice> to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilmR1">Wilmott Horton</persName> to gain him a<lb/>
               hearing from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BathH1">Lord Bathurst</persName> - &amp;<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28606_1826_11_08_page04.jpg"/>
               
               to give him the pleasure, which I<lb/>
               hope this note will procure him<lb/>
               of an hours conversation with<lb/>
               you - I think he will pay<lb/>
               you in information otherwise<lb/>
               I would not rob you of a morning<lb/>
               - as I know you do not <del>think</del>
               <lb/>
               <del>anybody</del> think it a pleasure<lb/>
               &amp; favor to be robbed of a <choice>
                  <abbr>morn<hi rend="superscript">g</hi>
                  </abbr>
                  <reg>morning</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StaeA1">Madame de Stael</persName> said <add>to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">Dumont</persName>
               </add> of McInJ1 <choice>
                  <orig>M<hi rend="superscript">c</hi>.<lb/>
                  Intosh</orig>
                  <reg>McIntosh</reg>
               </choice> - " Vous ne pouvez' lui<lb/>
               "faire un plus grand plaisir que<lb/>
               "lui voler une matinee" !! -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I heard this day from<lb/>
               M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <unclear>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoilJ1">Moilliet</persName>
               </unclear> that the depression<lb/>
               of Braz<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>. bonds has been a<lb/>
               Hack jobbing operation - that the<lb/>
               stability of the government is<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">unquestionable</hi> - that they (the<lb/>
               bonds I mean, must eventually<lb/>
               rise - (No reasons given) -<lb/>
               But I shall wait quietly -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I enclose for you a most<lb/>
               friendly letter from 
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GallA1">M. Gallatin</persName>
               <lb/>
               - I beg you will return it to me<lb/>
               as soon as you have swallowed<lb/>
               <unclear>it</unclear> - under cover to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#TaylT1">Earl of Bective<lb/>
               Headfort - Kells.</persName> - When you return it<lb/>
               please tell me whether you<lb/>
               would like to be acquainted with<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GallA1">Gallatin</persName> - My opinion is that<lb/>
               <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28606_1826_11_08_page05.jpg"/>
               
               you would mutually please &amp; suit each other<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName> takes an introductory note <unclear>from</unclear>
               <lb/>
               me - -<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BankX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Banks</persName> the traveller who has just paid £400 for<lb/>
               telling <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Buckingham-Palace_ENK">Buckingham</placeName> ses verités has been here<lb/>
               - on a visit to young <persName ref="./Personography.xml#XxxxA2">Alexander</persName> - at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Ardbraccan_IE">Ardbraccan</placeName>
               <lb/>
               - We dined there twice to meet him having<lb/>
               known him &amp; his drawings &amp; curiosities in<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName> - He recognised <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">me</persName> with <choice>
                  <orig>appa<lb/>
                  rently</orig>
                  <reg>apparently</reg>
               </choice> great satisfaction &amp; in the midst of a<lb/>
               great deal of entertaining conversation at<lb/>
               dinner, hurrying from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Athens_GR">Athens</placeName> to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Thebes_EG">Thebes</placeName> &amp;<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Thebes_EG">Thebes</placeName> to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Jerusalem_IL">Jerusalem</placeName> &amp; <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Jerusalem_IL">Jerusalem</placeName> to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Istanbul_TR">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Constan<lb/>
                  tinople</orig>
                     <reg>Constantinople</reg>
                  </choice>
               </placeName> - we got happily together to <title ref="./Workography.xml#Karam1">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Kara<lb/>
                     man<gap/>
                     </orig>
                     <reg>Karamania</reg>
                  </choice>
               </title> - about which he said so well at <gap/>
               <lb/>
                 so we<gap/>ing taste that I asked if he knew <gap/>
               <lb/>
               author - No - but he is a man I have often<lb/>
               desired to be acquainted -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I believe I could give you that pleasure<lb/>
               - if you wish it really - Really then I do -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <hi rend="underline">So</hi> I <hi rend="underline">said</hi> about your being <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. E</persName>'s brother &amp;c<lb/>
               - and left him with the ½ promise till I <choice>
                  <abbr>sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>
                  </abbr>
                  <reg>should</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
               make myself sure of what you like - If you<lb/>
               like to see <hi rend="underline">him</hi> &amp; his treasures - his newly<lb/>
               discovered <hi rend="underline">
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Petra_JO">Petra</placeName>
               </hi> &amp;c let me know - I have no<lb/>
               doubt he would <hi rend="underline">like</hi> shew <hi rend="underline">them</hi> &amp; <hi rend="underline">himself</hi>
               <lb/>
               to you - and as he is warm with gratitude<lb/>
               to me at present for the gift of an Irish<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">sepulchral urn</hi>
               <add>Alias - mouldered <unclear/> dried clay bowl which</add> I gave him, the sooner <del>you</del>
               <lb/>
               I strike the better - The first visit or card shall<lb/>
               come from him - so put your pride in your pocket</p>
            <lb/>
            <closer>
               &amp; believe me affectionately y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria E</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28606_1826_11_08_page06.jpg"/>
            <postscript>
               <p>I am sincerely<lb/>
                  sorry for <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LyonX1">Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>
                     <lb/>
               Lyons</persName> -<lb/>
               Your account<lb/>
               was most<lb/>
               shocking and<lb/>
               pathetic of the<lb/>
               loss of that<lb/>
               charming woman</p>
               <lb/>
            </postscript>
            <note>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">ME</persName> -<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ThomJ1">Thomson</persName>, <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GallA1">Gallatin</persName>
               <lb/>
               Banker<lb/>
               8 Nov<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. 26</note>
            <lb/>
            <closer>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>.. Beaufort</persName>R. N</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>
                     <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Manchester-Street-51_ENK">51 Manchester St<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
                     </placeName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <addrLine>
                     <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Manchster-Square_ENK">Manchester Sq</placeName>
                  </addrLine>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
